{"type":"message","id":"1c90198a","parentId":"dd54353b","timestamp":"2026-03-29T14:12:06.060Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Yes, but it's complicated. Here's the landscape: **YouTube Data API v3** - Does NOT include transcript/caption content - Only tells you IF captions exist (`contentDetails.caption`) - Can list caption tracks but not download them --- **YouTube's Internal Timedtext API** - URL: `https://www.youtube.com/api/timedtext?v=VIDEO_ID&lang=en` - This is what YouTube uses internally for their player - **Not official/documented** - breaks frequently - Requires parsing the video page to get caption track IDs first --- **Third-party Options:** | Service | Pros | Cons | |---------|------|------| | **yt-dlp** | Most reliable, free, open source | Requires local install | | **youtube-transcript-api** (Python) | Simple API, free | Unofficial, can break | | **AssemblyAI** | Official API, reliable | Paid, requires API key | | **RapidAPI YouTube Transcript** | Official-feeling API | Paid per request | --- **Recommendation:** The `youtube-transcript-api` Python package is the cleanest solution for programmatic access: ```bash pip install youtube-transcript-api ``` ```python from youtube_transcript_api import YouTubeTranscriptApi transcript = YouTubeTranscriptApi.get_transcript(\"VIDEO_ID\") text = \" \".join([t[\"text\"] for t in transcript]) ``` Want me to update the skill to use `youtube-transcript-api` instead of the timedtext approach? It's more reliable than what I implemented."}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"nvidia","model":"z-ai/glm5","usage":{"input":32823,"output":312,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":33135,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774793511551,"responseId":"chatcmpl-b7c1c8c89f919ceb"}}
